cat
Similar to tail in some way, we have cat. Except cat can also add content to a file, and this makes it super powerful.

In its simplest usage, cat prints a file's content to the standard output:

Bash
cat file
You can print the content of multiple files:

Bash
cat file1 file2
and using the output redirection operator > you can concatenate the content of multiple files into a new...

💡 Understanding the Full Power of cat
The name cat is short for concatenate (which means linking things together in a chain). While it's most commonly used just to quickly view a file, its true strength comes from joining files or creating them.

Here is how the cut-off part at the bottom of the slide works in practice:

1. Concatenating (Merging) Files
You can take the content of two separate files, merge them together sequentially, and save the result into a brand new third file:

Bash
cat file1 file2 > merged_file.txt
2. Creating a File and Writing Directly to It
If you run cat with the redirection operator but without specifying an input file, it will wait for you to type directly into the terminal:

Bash
cat > new_notes.txt
How it works: After running this, the terminal will give you a blank line. Type whatever text you want. When you are finished, press Ctrl + D on a new line to save and close the file.